âœ”ï¸ Create a closing ritual

Every Sunday after the last service, I hold my notes in my hand, thank God for the message, and dramatically throw them in the trash can.

You're more than a sermon. You're a child of God. Make sure you do something to remember what's most important.

âœ”ï¸ Pray

Don't just pray for your sermon (but please do). Pray for your anxious heart in this stressful week. Much of the pressure is self-inflicted. In prayer, God gives you perspective and comfort â€” and reminds you that HE is the Good Shepherd who saves sinners.

âœ”ï¸ Enjoy Jesus in front of people

I barely remember what I preached last Easter, let alone the years before. Nobody else does either. But they'll likely remember that Jesus seemed to you to be delightful. So make it your aim to publicly delight in Jesus.

âœ”ï¸ Make sure to be yourself

The pressure can make you want to be, as the kids say, "extra." Instead, be yourself and trust that God will use YOU just as you are.

âœ”ï¸ Give it a run-through

This is generally good advice, but I especially like to give a run-through because â€” with 5 Easter services â€” I have a shorter time limit. It helps to make sure I hit time and keeps me from practicing on the people.

âœ”ï¸ Make sense to kids and guests

With more kids and guests in the service than normal, communicate in a way that will engage and make sense to them. Skip the churchy jargon. Include a funny story that would grab a 2nd-grader's attention. Make them think, "I'd like to come back."

âœ”ï¸ Emphasize the cross on Good Friday, not on Easter

Too many Easter sermons sound like Good Friday sermons. Yes, the cross is glorious. But Easter is about Jesus' victory over death.

Of course, they go together ("the Christ event"). But make sure Easter feels like Easter.

âœ”ï¸  Don't get too cute

There's always a temptation to get overly "creative" for Easter. After all, it's a familiar story that you want to be interesting.

Resist that urge â€” this thing isn't about you and your ingenuity. Preach a simple, clear gospel message.
